{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510112"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11494"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11494"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.12,0.03,0.01,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49407"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4125"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"},{"type":"tags","id":"1340"},{"type":"tags","id":"1380"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11522"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43236"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49407"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 89-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her son, who is concerned about her poor memory over the last six months. She has a medical history of hypertension, transient ischaemic attack, hypercholesterolaemia, and urinary incontinence. Her medications include amlodipine, atorvastatin, and topical oestrogen. Her son reports that she often forgets daily tasks such as taking out the rubbish and turning off the lights when she leaves the house. The patient admits that she sometimes forgets what she has said in previous conversations with her friends. She is disheartened that she is slower at solving chess puzzles when she plays with her grandchildren. She is living at home independently and is able to perform all her daily and instrumental activities of daily living. The son has not noticed any changes to her mood in the past three months. She does not feel worried about her forgetfulness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has a normal gait. She is oriented to time, place and person. She has sound judgement and no disorganised thought on mental state examination. Her Mini-Mental State Examination score is 22/30 (points deducted in immediate memory, attention/concentration and delayed recall).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Vascular dementia","Pseudodementia","Lewy body dementia","Mild cognitive impairment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis elderly patient presents with short-term memory loss but maintains her full independent activities of daily living (ADLs). The cognitive defects have not interfered with the patient\u0027s daily independent ADLs; therefore, this would classify as \u003Cstrong\u003Emild cognitive impairment\u003C/strong\u003E. Mild cognitive impairment is the most likely diagnosis, albeit, there would be a need to exclude other causes of her presentation e.g. space-occupying lesion, hypothyroidism. Mild cognitive impairment usually suggests the preservation of independent ADLs but there may be evidence of a decline in one or more cognitive domains. It is important to note that mild cognitive impairment is not dementia, but identifies patients who are at risk of dementia. Mild cognitive impairment carries the increased risk of progression to Alzheimer\u0027s disease, however, it does not always progress. Management of mild cognitive impairment involves monitoring, educating the family on signs to look out for in dementia and excluding reversible causes of cognitive impairment i.e. B12/folate/iron deficiency, thyroid disease and cerebrovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a progressive cognitive impairment that is associated with memory loss. However, this does not meet the diagnostic criteria of Alzheimer\u0027s dementia due to the absence of impact on ADLs in this case. The patient\u0027s presentation could, however, represent the early symptoms of what will progress to clinical Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Therefore, annual Mini-Mental State Examinations are usually recommended to observe such cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is typically characterised by a stepwise decline in cognitive function, often with a history of stroke or cardiovascular risk factors. While this patient has a history of hypertension, transient ischaemic attack, and hypercholesterolaemia, which are risk factors for vascular dementia, her gradual onset of symptoms and preserved independence in ADLs make this diagnosis less likely at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudodementia\u003C/strong\u003E is a psychiatric disorder, such as depression, that mimics symptoms of dementia i.e. memory loss. However, this patient reports no depressed mood changes or other depressive symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body dementia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fluctuating cognition, visual hallucinations, and parkinsonian features. This patient does not exhibit these characteristic symptoms, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, despite the patient\u0027s vascular risk factors, the preservation of independence in ADLs, the specific cognitive deficits noted, and the absence of features suggestive of other forms of dementia or psychiatric conditions make mild cognitive impairment the most likely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mild cognitive impairment is characterised by evidence of impairment in \u22651 cognitive domain which is insufficient to interfere with independence in daily activities.","A dementia diagnosis requires interference with independence in activities of daily living."],"references":["Koepsell TD, Monsell SE. Reversion from mild cognitive impairment to normal or near-normal cognition: risk factors and prognosis. Neurology 2012; 79:1591.","Taylor WD. Clinical practice. Depression in the elderly. N Engl J Med 2014; 371:1228.","Petersen RC, Lopez O, Armstrong MJ, et al. Practice guideline update summary: Mild cognitive impairment: Report of the Guideline Development, Dissemination, and Implementation Subcommittee of the American Academy of Neurology. Neurology 2018; 90:126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-28T21:24:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-28T21:24:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4125"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49407"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api